Title: Git and GitHub Short Notes

1. Introduction to Git
   Git is a distributed version control system used to track changes in source code during software development. It allows multiple developers to work on the same project without conflicts.

2. Features of Git

* Tracks code changes
* Supports branching and merging
* Distributed version control
* Enables collaboration among developers

3. What is GitHub
   GitHub is a cloud-based platform that hosts Git repositories. It allows developers to store, manage, and collaborate on projects using Git.

4. Difference Between Git and GitHub
   Git:

* A version control tool
* Works locally on a computer
* Tracks code history

GitHub:

* A web-based platform
* Stores repositories online
* Supports team collaboration

5. Important Git Commands
   git init – Initialize a new Git repository
   git clone – Copy a repository from GitHub
   git add – Add files to staging area
   git commit – Save changes in the repository
   git push – Upload local changes to GitHub
   git pull – Download updates from GitHub
   git branch – Show or create branches
   git checkout – Switch between branches
   git merge – Combine branches

6. What is a Repository
   A repository (repo) is a storage location for project files and their version history.

7. What is a Branch
   A branch is a separate version of the code where developers can make changes without affecting the main project.

8. What is a Pull Request
   A pull request is a request to merge code changes from one branch into another branch after review.

9. Benefits of Using Git and GitHub

* Easy collaboration
* Version tracking
* Backup of project code
* Efficient team development

10. Conclusion
    Git and GitHub are essential tools for modern software development. They help developers manage code, track changes, and collaborate effectively.
